{"key":"post-17172228","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17172228</id>\n<content>Yes, the 8&quot; should be sufficient.&amp;nbsp; If you find a blower which will deliver 500 to 600 cfm at .5&quot; to .6&quot; W.G., you'll be fine.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You want to account for 'resistance' of the prefilter, but no static pressure since none develops.&amp;nbsp; I use a super allergen by 3M and have been running the same flow hood filter several hours daily for over a decade with no loss in flow.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I was told my filter has a static pressure of .4&quot; at 400CFM and 1&quot; at 1000 CFM.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This simply means if you develop .4&quot; of static pressure in the plenum, your flow rate will be 400 cfm, and if you develop 1&quot; of static pressure in the plenum behind the filter, you'll get 1000 cfm.&amp;nbsp; I would be suspicious though, because I've not seen a linear correlation between static pressure and flow before.&amp;nbsp; Be sure to check the chart with the filter before buying a blower.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17172345</next>\n<prev>17172179</prev>\n<first>17171020</first>\n<last>17173237</last>\n<when>1352229219</when>\n<utime>11/06/12 09:13 PM</utime>\n</post>"}